LONDON Platinum producer Lonmin re-opened two of its shafts in South Africa on 20 May after community protests stopped, a spokeswoman said on Wednesday.The E2 and E3 shafts, which were temporarily closed after the community demanded jobs at the mine, were fully opened on Saturday but had been paused after the death of a local chief, spokeswoman Wendy Tlou said.READ: Lonmin E2, E3 NWest shafts to remain closed for nowThe two shafts, which closed on 3 May, contribute 3 to 4 percent of total production.Lonmin has been in talks with Bapo ba Mogale Traditional Council and unemployed youth after they staged protests outside the company s shafts since the beginning of May.Reuters